A better method is to look at distance over time.  If a car behind you
in the left lane is closing on you, and then eventually reaches you and
needs to slow down to not hit you, if you had time anywhere up to the
point the guy is right behind you (or it soon opens up), and you don't
pull to the right, you are lane blocking.

It's really as simple as this:  You can stay in the left lane as long as
you want, as long as the lanes to the right of you aren't, in general,
passing you, or there isn't someone behind you in the left lane who was
clearly going faster than you before they reached you.  As soon as it's
clear the driver behind you wants to go faster than you, you pull to the
right as soon as safely possible.

I think what a lot of people are doing wrong is that they assume just
because you pull to the right, doesn't mean you can't immediately go
back in the left lane once the faster driver(s) pass you.  I do it all
the time; if I see a long line of cars in the non-left-lane I'm in that
I want to pass, I'll pull into the left lane and try to pass them all at
once.  If I notice someone getting close to me, as soon as I see an
opening I can pull into towards the right, I will until that driver
passes me.  If I still want to pass more cars, I go in the left lane as
if I were just pulling into that lane for the first time.

Also, cruise control...  I think part of the problem is that people who
use cruise control in the left lane (and are going faster than those in
the right lane(s)) don't understand that they can just step on the gas
to temporarily go faster to get around people so that they can yield to
faster drivers behind them in the left lane.
