I am driving 85 in a 70 zone (people do it all the time on
I-95 in NC). I am approaching a car doing 45 (the legal
minimum). How far back should I begin to change lanes? Your
suggestion says I should begin to change lanes 8.5 car
lenghts behind the slower vehicle. This is around 135 feet.
It will take about 2.3 sec to close the gap between the two
cars with a 40 mph closing velocity. Don't you think it
would be better to move over sooner? At least give the guy
in the slower car a chance to realize what is happening.
Also, many times if I wait until I am only 10 car leght per
10 mph behind another vehicle, someone in the line behind me
will jump out into the left lane first, leaving me to decide
whether it is OK to pull over in the left lane in front of
the other car (which is often a cowardly duckling using me
as a shield), or that I need to get on the brakes hard to
fall in behind the slower car so that the lane jumper can
go. And if I actually jump on the brakes to fall in, doing
so will cause all the ducklings behind me to slow down
immeadiately, slowing the whole process down. So, at leaste
for this example (which you are free to claim is a straw
man, but I won't agree), I think your suggested lane
changing distance is not a good one. I'd prefer to move over
about 5 sec before I reach a much slower moving vehicle I
plan to pass. In my example, this would be about 300 feet
behind the slower car. For cars at close to the same speed
(like me doing 70, the other car doing 65), I'd be inclined
to follow your rule.

I have no problem with moving left to pass...but how do you
handle this situation -

I am driving 70 in a 70 zone (nice and legal). I catch up to
a tractor-trailer rig doing 65 (again legal) in the right
lane. As I get ready to pass the slower vehicle, there is
another car more than 250 yards (750 feet) behind me that is
doing 85 (illegal, but routine). At that distance, it is not
so easy to determine the closing rate of the car behind me.
I pull out to pass the slower vehicle when I am 7 car
lenghts behind (110 feet), at which point the 85 mph vehicle
is 250 yards behind me, also in the right lane. I pass the
truck and pull back in when I am 7 car lenghts ahead (110
feet) Assume a single trailer rig of 55 ft lenght for the
truck. Total time to pass the big rig would be about 38 sec.
However during this 38 sec, the 85 mph car would have caught
me and had to wait for approximately 2 sec for me to
complete my pass. Is it reasonable for me to expect the 85
mph driver to wait at extra 2 sec to complete my pass? Or
should I wait 34 sec for the 85 mph car to catch me and then
wait another 5 sec for the 85 mph car to get 7 car lenghts
ahead before I begin my pass. During these 39 sec, I'd be
travelling at 65 mph instead of 70 mph, so I have lost
around 3 sec myself. To net it out, is there any rule either
by statute, morals, or common courtesy that says someone
breaking the law has a right to expect me to lose 3 seconds
of travel time so they can save 2 seconds of travel time?

And yeah, you can claim this is a straw man...but I don't
believe it is. It is an example of what can happen.

Again, it seems to me that all the "sloth kills" and "krep"
terrorist want to simplfy everything down to one simple rule
- "stay the hell out of my way."

