Eh, somewhat.  There is always a subset of people who will always obey
the speed limit, no matter whether it's reasonable or not.  In the case
of an underposted limit, this will actually have a safety-detrimental
effect of *increasing* speed differentials.  However, this effect is
probably very slight overall.  Additionally, let's say that the 85th
percentile speed of a road is 75 MPH.  If it's posted at 55 MPH but a
particular driver's personal comfort speed on that road is 80 MPH, he
will likely drive 80 MPH.  He's certainly not going to drive 55 (since
nobody else is anyway.)  However, if the road is posted at 75 MPH, he
may be more likely to obey the limit, since slowing down by 5 MPH is
not that big of a sacrifice (as opposed to slowing by 25 MPH.)  Again,
this has the overall effect of decreasing speed differentials, which is
a positive thing.

