We actually do have "lane discipline" in California, but the Lane
Discipline Nazis usually don't know it. Lane discipline is enforced on
the spot by professional truckers in the two right hand lanes. They
know they can't get away with much, the California Highway Patrol will
stop them before they will stop an idiot speeder in the "fast lane"...

Here in California, we have several mountain passes where the trucks
are restricted from driving in any lane except the two right hand
lanes. In fact, trucks are restricted to the two right lanes on any
freeway, unless they need to be in a lane further to the left in order
to proceeed along their intended route. Too bad if a speeding Lane
Discipline Nazi doesn't like that!

As the big trucks begin the 3000 foot climb out of the San Joaquin
valley to to the 4400 foot Tejon summit, I often see heavily laden
trucks laboring along in low gear in the right lane going 25 mph or
less and the less heavily laden trucks will be passing them at maybe 35
mph in the second from the right lane.
In the minds of some Lane Discipline Nazis, the trucks shouldn't be on
the highways at all, they should be a "special road" for trucks, out of
sight of the automobile drivers...

It only takes a car about 10 minutes or so, driving at the speed limit
to reach the summit, maybe it take the trucks twice as long...

It takes a little bit of planning and alertness on the part of
automobile drivers to remember to push the accelerator pedal down, and
perhaps even downshift into passing gear to get up that grade. Many
have probably never intentionally selected their passing gear for
climbing grades or descending grades in their entire lives. They don't
realize they can even *do* that, they are very skeptical when told that
it's really OK to move the shift lever into another position besides
"Drive"...

Some "fast lane" drivers who've been cruising at 80 mph on the flat
will find themselves suddenly bogged down at 60, or even 55 mph as they
try to go up the grade in a "Drive" position that is very tall geared
for fuel economy...

Alert, enthusiastic drivers who've been up the grade before try to
attack it at high speed. They hope to go up the grade at 80 mph, just
as fast as they cruised on the flat. They probably wouldn't use their
passing gear on the grade either...

When they see the less-than-alert drivers bogged down at 55 or 60 mph,
they start zigging-and-zagging around the "slowpokes". Sometimes one of
the speed enthusiasts trying to climb the grade at 70 or 80 mph would
find he's made a mistake, he gets stuck behind a big truck going 25 or
35 mph, and that will make him angry at all the "stupid slowpokes" that
spoiled his drive. After crossing over the pass at Tejon summit, he'll
drive 80 or 90 mph all the way down to the San Fernando valley. Boy,
that will sure teach those "stupid slowpokes" a lesson in who's "boss",
won't it?

Going down the Tejon grade towards Grapevine is even scarier. Gravity
is working for the dullest-witted drivers. The heavily-laden trucks are
restricted to the two right hand lanes at a limit of 35 mph. You can
see clouds of smoke coming off of brakes and smell burning brakes for
ten miles coming off the Tejon Summit into the San Joaquin valley...

But the speeding scofflaws are passing those trucks at 80 mph going
down that steep grade. Gawd help one of those fools if a runaway truck
needs to use the escape road on the center median. And gawd help them
if a big-rig should lose control and jack knife across all lanes of
traffic descending the grade...

If more than one truck should happen to break down ascending or
descending the Tejon pass, the truckers are going to just move over one
more lane and use that lane to pass slower trucks. Then there's only
ONE lane left for the speeders and the law-abiding drivers. Maybe it
makes the Lane Discipline Nazis cry to have to slow down a little, but
nobody cares if their little feelings are hurt...

As I descend the Tejon Pass, I stay the heck out of the "fast lane" and
watch my rear view mirror for fools approaching from behind. I'm still
driving 30 mph faster than the law-abiding trucks beside me, and an
exploding overloaded truck tire could frag my little pickup with chunks
of flying rubber, fabric and wire...

That might ruin my underwear...
