supposedly "blocking" the #1 lane would have to make unsafe lane
changes and FORCE their way into the line of traffic in the #2 lane to
get there at all. It's highly unlikely that a whole line of faster cars
would be able to proceed for very far in the #2 lane during rush
hour...

The drivers bunched up behind the driver cruising at the speed limit
can't be speeding, but they are following each other too closely. They
are in violation of the Basic Speed Law that says you can't drive
faster than is safe. There are recommended following distances of about
2 or 3 seconds behind the car ahead...

The law-abiding driver should be from 190 to 286 feet beyond the car
ahead of him, but that safety cushion just isn't going to exist for
long with the impatient scofflaw drivers driving at excessive speed to
the right of the law-abiding driver. They are going to try to jam as
many of their cars into that space as possible, then they are going to
harass and tail gate each other as they continue down the road, trying
to force their way through the situation instead of relaxing and
obeying the speed laws and respecting each other's right to to use the
road lawfully...

The asshats passing on the right are going to jump into the law-abiding
driver's recommended safety cushion so they can continue to drive like
asshats...

And the law-abiding driver cruising in the #1 lane at the legal speed
limit is *NOT* slower traffic. The three axled trucks and two-axled
vehicles towing trailers are the "slower traffic" referred to by the
"SLOWER TRAFFIC KEEP RIGHT"
sign. If they are driving in lanes to the left of the two righthand
lanes, they may be cited unless the reason for being in another lane
besides the two righthand lanes is that they need to use, say, the #2
lane to continue on their planned route. But they are restricted to
driving at a maximum of 55 mph, and they are NOT illegal if they are
slowing the poor little speeders down below the 75 or 80 mph they would
like to believe they had the right to drive at...

If you carefully read CVC 21654(a) and (b) you will figure out that the
law-abiding driver in the lefthand lane only has to drive at the speed
limit or be passing *any other* vehicle and he can remain there for as
long as he wants...

If he's driving 65 in 65 zone, and the slower moving 3-axle trucks and
2-axle vehicles in the #3 and #4 lanes are driving at 55mph, there's no
lawful reason that the law-abiding driver has to move over to the right
for the scofflaws, since he is in the act of passing somebody slower
ALL THE TIME...

The business in CVC 21654(a) about "not withstanding the prima facie
speed limits" means that he can't defend himself by saying that he was
driving slower than the speed limit because it was "unsafe" to drive
that fast. The business about "normal speed in that situation" cannot
be interpreted to say that "normal speed" is a speed in excess of the
maximum speed limit, but "normal speed" might be much less than the
speed limit...

And, competent evidence to defend the law-abiding driver against a
citation of failing to move to the right would likely be nothing more
than a photograph of an existing speed limit sign and perhaps a speedo
calibration slip from AAA...
