California's Basic Speed Law takes precedence over the so-called "prima
facie"
speed limits of 15, 25, or 35 mph authorized by CVC 22352. It also
takes precedence over the 55 or 65 or 70 mph limits authorized in CVC
22349 and
CVC 22356. CVC 22348 says that a speeder just isn't going to get away
with violating the maximum speed limits by presenting competent
evidence in accordance with CVC 22351(b), which might be used to get
away with violating lesser prima facie limits such as those in CVC
22352...

Basic Speed Law CVC 22350.   No person shall drive a vehicle upon a
highway at a speed greater than is reasonable or prudent having due
regard for weather, visibility, the traffic on, and the surface and
width of, the highway, and in no event at a speed which endangers the
safety of persons or property.

So, the prima facie speed limit on a highway might be 35 mph, but if
there are a bunch of pedestrians running out into the street, the Basic
Speed Law prevails. The prima facie speed to drop to 5 mph. It could
drop to zero mph.

There might be other problems on the highway, weather, free range
cattle running loose, construction equipment, slower traffic, etc., but
motorists have come to believe that the MAXIMUM speed limit is a
MINIMUM speed limit and that they can push the limit as they please,
they will just *force* their way through all situations with the pedal
to the metal...

When combined with the urban myth that the lefthand lane is some sort
of "fast lane" or is always a "passing lane", this notion of the
maximum speed limit plus X number of miles per hour that busy traffic
cops will ignore leads to conflicts or collisions between motorists.

The highest speed authorized on any highway is contained in the
California Vehicle Code, which does not define "normal speed of
traffic" at all. Therefore, "normal speed of traffic" cannot possibly
be higher than what is authorized...

Speed Law Violations

22351.   (a) The speed of any vehicle upon a highway not in excess of
the limits specified in Section 22352 or established as authorized in
this code is lawful unless clearly proved to be in violation of the
basic speed law.

(b) The speed of any vehicle upon a highway in excess of the prima
